A policy needs to be determined as to how the Metadata Type Specifications are kept synchronised across the distribution network given that this domain is likely to be deployed at many (if not all) the nodes in that network. Two candidate solutions might be:
  1. Should there be an additional required interface that provides an operation to invoke a synchronising service to achieve this? - in which case, this sequence diagram would need to be extended to call this operation at this point.
  2. The alternative is that an architectural service is built in to ensure that all classes stereotyped <<synchronised>> are automatically synchronised across the network whenever a change is detected in any of the nodes where this component is deployed.
This issue would need to be resolved for all the other specification classes in this domain which have been stereotyped <<synchronised>>.

A node in the distribution network that a Message that is generated or received in one node is forwarded on to.

The Messages domain provides a service to allow any client to log a message. It achieves this by providing a number of generic operations on its Logging interface that are independent of any specific client needs. As such, the client's message logging requirement (including any message parameters) will need to be mapped onto the appropriate interface operation (and its associated operation parameters). The creation of this mapping specification is the responsibility of a System Integrator. In order to achieve this, the System Integrator needs to have visibility of the structure of the Message Types defined within this domain. The output of this Use Case is the Client Message-to-Message Log mapping specification (which can then be realised in the respective bridge mapping (client required interface to Messages provided interface mapping). As such, there is no sequence diagram that describes the user-interactions to develop this mapping specification.

properties.documentation:
Messages generated by any client of this component can be submitted and logged for subsequent viewing or analysis. Before each Message is logged it is validated against the respective Message Type specification. Valid Messages are:
  • Saved to the Message Log
  • Automatically forwarded to other nodes where needed.
  • Alerted to all users who have subscribed to Messages of the respective Message Type.
  • Confirmed as logged to the respective Message Generator.
Invalid Messages are rejected and the respective Message Generator notified with a reason for rejection.

Provides the means to modify any aspect of an existing Message Type, including:
  1. Change the description
  2. Change the message category
  3. Change the sequence of Field Types (and their individual characteristics - e.g. optionality, repeatability, etc.)
  4. Change the Network Nodes that logged Messages of the respective Message Type should be forwarded to.
Important Note: The name of the Message Type cannot be modified (as currently modelled) because the name of the Message Type is declared as the identifier and is thus immutable. As an alternative, it would be possible to give each Message Type an arbitrary, integer-based identifier and allow the name to be changed.

Received Messages that have been forwarded to a Network Node from another Network Node will <u>preserve </u>the original source.

Messages of a particular type can be configured such that not only are they captured as Message instances within this domain but are also forwarded to other nodes in the distribution network - this might be for numerous reasons including:
  • Resilience purposes - such that multiple copies of the Message are maintained
  • Further analysis - where the Message might be aggregated with other Messages from other nodes to detect 'interesting' behaviour across the network.
